  "answer": "**Cynewulf's runic signature in *Elene* appears at the poem's close as a hidden acrostic woven into the text.** The final passage embeds Old English runes that spell out his name (ᚳᚣᚾᛖᚹᚢᛚᚠ, or *Cyn(e)wulf*) across successive lines, a subtle claim of authorship disguised amid a meditation on transience and judgment.[^1]\n\n**Yājñavalkya's *Smṛti* opens by invoking a chain of prior sages and teachers as sources of *dharma*, positioning the text within an explicit tradition.** The rishis first honor Yājñavalkya before requesting instruction; he then lists eighteen prior Dharmaśāstra authors (e.g., Manu, Viṣṇu, Uśanas), establishing a public lineage of transmission from Vedic smṛti authorities.[^2]\n\n**Cynewulf's technique makes the text harder to forge.** A hidden rune acrostic demands precise replication of letter-sequence, meter, alliteration, and meaning—any alteration risks breaking the poem's form or exposing the signature, alerting copyists or scholars. Yājñavalkya's overt name-chain, while authoritative, is easily appended or edited (e.g., inserting fictitious sages), as ancient manuscripts often vary such colophons without disrupting core content.\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraphs](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-d2e607) through [paragraphs](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-dcbbfe).\n\n[^2]: Yājñavalkya, *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-97f0a4) through [paragraph](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-95ef53).",
